    "intro": "Embedded C is an extension of the C programming language that is used to develop software for microcontrollers and embedded devices. Unlike standard C, it requires an understanding of hardware registers, memory mapping, and real-time constraints.",
    "sections": [
        {
            "title": "The \"Hello World\" of Embedded: LED Blink",
            "text": "In embedded systems, the first program is usually toggling a GPIO pin to blink an LED. Below is a generic register-level example.",
            "code": {
                "lang": "Embedded C",
                "content": "// Example: Toggling a Pin on Port B (Pin 5)\n#include <stdint.h>\n\n#define PORTB_REG  (*((volatile uint32_t *)0x40020414))\n#define PIN5       (1 << 5)\n\nint main(void) {\n    // Configure hardware here...\n    \n    while(1) {\n        PORTB_REG ^= PIN5; // Toggle Pin 5 using XOR\n        for(volatile int i = 0; i < 100000; i++); // Software Delay\n    }\n    return 0;\n}"
            },
            "info": "The volatile keyword is crucial in Embedded C to prevent the compiler from optimizing out loops or variables that represent hardware registers."
        },
        {
            "title": "Embedded C vs. Standard C",
            "list": [
                "Hardware Dependency: Embedded C interacts directly with I/O ports and registers.",
                "Resources: Embedded systems have limited RAM and Flash (ROM).",
                "No OS: Often runs \"Bare Metal\" without an operating system.",
                "Infinite Loops: Embedded programs typically never exit (`while(1)`)."
            ]
        }
    ],
